## Impact

## Impact

Any TLS server running Node.js v26.3.0 that registers an `OCSPRequest` or `resumeSession` listener is vulnerable. If the listener throws under any condition â€” including expected error cases like a failed OCSP lookup or a cache miss during session resumption â€” a remote client can crash the server by sending the appropriate TLS extension. No authentication is required. The crash is deterministic and repeatable.

Real-world listeners commonly throw in these scenarios:
- `OCSPRequest`: network call to a CA fails and an exception is thrown instead of calling `cb(err)`
- `resumeSession`: a session store (Redis, Memcached) client is not yet connected and accessing it throws

---

## Suggested Fix

Wrap both vulnerable emits in `try/catch` blocks, calling `socket.destroy(err)` or `owner.destroy(err)` on catch â€” identical to what was done for `SNICallback` in the March 2026 patch.

**`requestOCSP()` â€” line 324-328:**
```js
debug('server oncertcb emit OCSPRequest');
try {
  socket.server.emit('OCSPRequest',
                     ctx.getCertificate(),
                     ctx.getIssuer(),
                     onOCSP);
} catch (err) {
  socket.destroy(err);
}
```

**`loadSession()` â€” line 193-203:**
```js
try {
  if (hello.sessionId.length <= 0 ||
      hello.tlsTicket ||
      (owner.server &&
      !owner.server.emit('resumeSession', hello.sessionId, onSession))) {
    owner._handle.endParser();
  }
} catch (err) {
  owner.destroy(err);
}
```

